1. Introduction ¶

In astronomy, stellar classification is the classification of stars based on their spectral characteristics. The classification scheme of galaxies, quasars, and stars is one of the most fundamental in astronomy. The early cataloguing of stars and their distribution in the sky has led to the understanding that they make up our own galaxy and, following the distinction that Andromeda was a separate galaxy to our own, numerous galaxies began to be surveyed as more powerful telescopes were built. This datasat aims to classificate stars, galaxies, and quasars based on their spectral characteristics.

The dataset consists of 100,000 observations of space taken by the SDSS (Sloan Digital Sky Survey). Every observation is described by 17 feature columns and 1 class column which identifies it to be either a star, galaxy or quasar.

Features

  1. obj_ID = Object Identifier, the unique value that identifies the object in the image catalog used by the CAS

  2. alpha = Right Ascension angle (at J2000 epoch)

  3. delta = Declination angle (at J2000 epoch)

  4. u = Ultraviolet filter in the photometric system

  5. g = Green filter in the photometric system

  6. r = Red filter in the photometric system

  7. i = Near Infrared filter in the photometric system

  8. z = Infrared filter in the photometric system

  9. run_ID = Run Number used to identify the specific scan

  10. rereun_ID = Rerun Number to specify how the image was processed

  11. cam_col = Camera column to identify the scanline within the run

  12. field_ID = Field number to identify each field

  13. spec_obj_ID = Unique ID used for optical spectroscopic objects (this means that 2 different observations with the same spec_obj_ID must share the output class)

  14. class = object class (galaxy, star or quasar object)

  15. redshift = redshift value based on the increase in wavelength

  16. plate = plate ID, identifies each plate in SDSS

  17. MJD = Modified Julian Date, used to indicate when a given piece of SDSS data was taken

  18. fiber_ID = fiber ID that identifies the fiber that pointed the light at the focal plane in each observation

4. Supervised Learning Techniques ¶

Supervised learning is a type of machine learning in which a model is trained on labeled examples to make predictions about new, unseen data. In supervised learning, the goal is to learn a function that maps input data to output labels, based on a labeled training set of examples.

Libraries and functions used in this chapter:

In [66]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingClassifier, AdaBoostClassifier, RandomForestClassifier, ExtraTreesClassifier
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_score, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, accuracy_score, classification_report

def evaluate_model_cv(model, x_train, y_train, cv=10):
  scores = cross_val_score(model, x_train, y_train, cv=cv)
  print("Cross-validation scores:", scores)
  print("Mean score:", np.mean(scores))
  print("Standard deviation:", np.std(scores))

def grid_search(grid, estimator, x_train, y_train,cv=10):
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=estimator, param_grid=grid, scoring='accuracy', verbose=5,cv=cv)
    grid_result = grid_search.fit(x_train, y_train)
    print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))
    return grid_result.best_estimator_

def test_and_conf(name, model, x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test):
  model.fit(x_train, y_train)
  y_pred = model.predict(x_test)
  print(f"Accuracy Score for {name} is : ",(model.score(x_test, y_test)) *100, "%")
  report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
  print(f'{name} model classification report:')
  print(report)
  cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
  cm_df = pd.DataFrame(cm, index=['GALAXY', 'STAR', 'QSO'], columns=['GALAXY', 'STAR','QSO'])
  print(f'{name} model confusion matrix:')
  sns.heatmap(cm_df, annot=True, fmt='d')

4.1 Model selection ¶

All the process needed for the application of the supervised learning techniques have been applied.

To predict stars, galaxies and quasars, I employed nine different supervised learning methods from different machine learning areas. The classifiers include the Logistic Regression, an instance - based learning model (k-Nearest Neighbors), two ensemble meta-estimator (Bagging Classifier and AdaBoost Classifier), an algorithms under the Gradient Boosting framework (XGB Classifier), tree - based methods (Random Forests, Decision Trees and Extra Trees), and a probabilistic classifiers called GaussianNB. The framework that I used to try the models is always the same for each model.

At first I used the evaluate_model_cv, a function that uses the cross_val_score function from the sklearn.model_selection module to evaluate the model on the training set using cross-validation. It then prints the cross-validation scores, the mean score, and the standard deviation of the scores.

At second I used the grid_search function that work strictly with a paramters grid. It uses the GridSearchCV function from the sklearn.model_selection module to perform grid search; the function prints the best score and the best hyperparameters found by the grid search, and returns the best estimator found by the search.

At the end I used the test_and_conf function that tests a machine learning model on a test set and displays a confusion matrix of the model's performance. Confusion matrices are a useful tool for evaluating the performance of a classification model, as they provide a detailed breakdown of the number of correct and incorrect predictions made by the model.

4.2 Achieved results and further application ¶

The results obtained by the supervised learning techniques outline that all the method with the function grid_search applied have an accuracy above the 90%, that is very solid. By considering all the machine learning models used, the best results are achieved by the XGB Classifier, with an accuracy of 98,23%.

Is important to notice that these results have been carried out with the balanced dataset thanks to the SMOTE technique. It would be nice to discover the behaviour of the machine learning models with the imbalanced dataset.

5. Unsupervised Learning Techniques ¶

Unsupervised learning techniques, such as clustering and dimensionality reduction, are used to discover patterns and relationships in the data without the use of labeled examples. Our work is to remove the class object from the dataset and then assign the remanining features to a variable that will be used as data for the principal component analysis.

Libraries used in this topic:

In [36]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

Preparing the data for the process.

In [37]:
Features = data.drop(["class"], axis = 1).columns
X = data[Features]

5.1 Principal Component Analysis ¶

PCA is often used as a preprocessing step before applying machine learning algorithms, especially usupervised learning models, to the data, as it can help to reduce the complexity of the data and improve the performance of the algorithms. It can also be used for data visualization, as it can help to reduce the dimensions of high-dimensional data to a lower number of dimensions that can be visualized on a 2D or 3D plot.

In the following box it is possible to see the application of PCA.

In [38]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)
X_pca = PCA(n_components = 2).fit_transform(X_scaled)
X_pca.shape
Out[38]:
(99999, 2)

After the scaling of the data the code applies PCA to the scaled data, with the number of components set to 2. This will transform the data into a new set of 2 dimensions, which are the principal components that capture the most variance in the data.

5.2 K-means ¶

K-means is used to group data points into clusters based on their similarity. It works by iteratively assigning each data point to the cluster with the nearest mean, and then updating the cluster means to the mean of the data points assigned to that cluster. The process is repeated until the cluster assignments no longer change, or some other stopping criterion is met.

In this case, a list is used to save the silhoutte score and the number of clusters is set to the variable i that ranges from 2 to 10.

In [39]:
sc = []
for i in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = Pipeline([("scaling", StandardScaler()), ("clustering", KMeans(n_clusters = i, init = 'k-means++', max_iter = 20, n_init = 10, random_state = 0))]).fit(X)
    score = silhouette_score(X, kmeans["clustering"].labels_)
    sc.append(score)
plt.plot(range(2, 10), sc, marker = "o")
plt.title('Silhouette', fontsize = 22)
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters', fontsize = 15)
plt.ylabel('Score', fontsize = 15)
plt.show()

In our case, we have 3 classes: stars, galaxies and quasars. One possible reason why the silhouette score is highest for 2 clusters is that the data may not be well-suited for k-means clustering. K-means assumes that the data consists of a fixed number of spherical clusters, and it may not be able to accurately identify more complex patterns in the data.

It's also possible that the data is simply not well-separated into distinct clusters, and no matter how many clusters you use, the silhouette score will not be very high. In this case, k-means may not be the best clustering method our data.

In the following box there is the print of all the possible clusters with k that ranges from 2 to 10, according to the previous value of i. As it can be observed the printing phase goes until 9 clusters, and it is based on the first component and the second component of the PCA.

In [40]:
for k in range (2,10):
 kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
 clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(X_pca)
 # Create a scatterplot of the PCA output
 plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=clusters, cmap='viridis')
 plt.xlabel('First component')
 plt.ylabel('Second component')
 plt.title('PCA output with k-means clusters with k={}'.format(k))
 plt.show()

Unfortunately is not possible to try other clustering methods due to computational power.

6. Semi-supervised Learning Techniques ¶

Semi-supervised learning is a machine learning technique that involves training a model using a combination of labeled and unlabeled data. In a supervised learning scenario, the model is trained using a labeled dataset, where the input data is accompanied by its corresponding label or output. In contrast, in an unsupervised learning scenario, the model is only provided with input data and no labels.

Semi-supervised learning lies in between these two approaches, as it uses a combination of labeled and unlabeled data to train the model. This is useful in situations where it is expensive or time-consuming to label a large dataset, but a small amount of labeled data is still available.

In this chapter you will see the application of semi-supervised learning techniques like the label propagation and co-training.

Libraries used:

In [69]:
from sklearn.semi_supervised import LabelPropagation

6.1 Label Propagation ¶

Label propagation is a semi-supervised learning technique that involves propagating labels from a small set of labeled data points to a larger set of unlabeled data points in order to classify them. It is based on the idea that data points that are close to each other in the feature space are likely to have similar labels.

In the following code the 90% of labels have been removed to apply the semi supervised technique.

In [70]:
n_labeled = int(len(x_train) * 0.1)
X_train_labeled = x_train[:n_labeled]
y_train_labeled = y_train[:n_labeled]
X_train_unlabeled = x_train[n_labeled:]

The data are now prepared for the execution of label propagation. In the following box it can be observed that there is the cration of the label propagation model and his fit to the labeled training data. In other words I am using the model to label the unlabeled training data and then combine the labeled and unlabeled data for training.

In [71]:
lp = LabelPropagation(kernel = 'rbf', gamma = 20)
lp.fit(X_train_labeled, y_train_labeled)
y_train_pred = lp.predict(X_train_unlabeled)
X_train_combined = np.concatenate([X_train_labeled, X_train_unlabeled])
y_train_combined = np.concatenate([y_train_labeled, y_train_pred])

After the preparation of the model, there is the training of classifiers, in this case the DecisionTreeClassifier and the LogisticRegression, on the combined labeled and unlabeled data and make prediction on the test set.

In [76]:

6.2 Co-training ¶

Co-training is a semi-supervised learning method that involves training two classifiers on different views of the data, and iteratively labeling additional examples using the predictions of the two classifiers. The goal of co-training is to improve the performance of the classifiers by leveraging the complementary information present in the different views of the data.

In this case the starting part is related to the split of data into two views; the classifiers are trained on these views using the labeled data. The labeled and unlabeled examples are stored in the lists.

In [46]:
X_view1, X_view2, y_view1, y_view2 = train_test_split(x_train, y_train, test_size=0.5)
ctr1 = RandomForestClassifier()
ctr2 = DecisionTreeClassifier()
ctr1.fit(X_view1, y_view1)
ctr2.fit(X_view2, y_view2)
labeled = [(X_view1, y_view1), (X_view2, y_view2)]
unlabeled = [(x_test, y_test)]

The co-training loop then iterates until all examples in unlabeled are labeled or a stopping criteria is met. In each iteration, the classifier trained on one view predicts the labels for the examples in the other view, and these examples are added to the list of labeled examples. The classifiers are then retrained on the newly labeled examples and the stopping criteria is checked.

In [78]:
while len(unlabeled) > 0:
    X_unlabeled, y_unlabeled = unlabeled.pop()
    y_pred = ctr2.predict(X_unlabeled)
    labeled.append((X_unlabeled, y_pred))
    if len(unlabeled) > 0:
      X_unlabeled, y_unlabeled = unlabeled.pop()
      y_pred = ctr1.predict(X_unlabeled)
      labeled.append((X_unlabeled, y_pred))
    X = np.concatenate(X)
    y = np.concatenate(y)
    ctr1.fit(X, y)
    ctr2.fit(X, y)
    
accuracy1 = ctr1.score(x_test, y_test)
accuracy2 = ctr2.score(x_test, y_test)

Finally, the accuracy of the classifier on the test set.

In [80]:
print(f'Accuracy of classifier 1: {accuracy1:.2f}')
print(f'Accuracy of classifier 2: {accuracy2:.2f}')

Accuracy of classifier 1: 0.98
Accuracy of classifier 2: 0.97

Before these results I tried to employ the same classifier for both the views and I obtained the same accuracy; this is not always an error in co-training, but it could indicate that co-training is not providing any benefit over training a single classifier on the full dataset.

Possible reasons why the classifiers have the same accuracy could be that:

  • the views of the data are highly correlated, so the classifiers trained on each view are making the same predictions. In this case, the classifiers may be redundant and co-training may not provide any benefit over training a single classifier on the full dataset

  • the classifiers are not learning from the labeled examples. This could be due to poor quality or insufficient quantity of labeled examples, or to a problem with the classifiers themselves (such as a lack of capacity or overfitting).

7. Comparison with other studies ¶

It could be optimal to compare the outcomes of this project with other studies that can be found on Kaggle on the similar dataset.

Since that the analysis for this dataset is, for most of the times, the same for all the notebooks in Kaggle, I will take the first notebook in term of preferences, and it is the one of Batucan Senkal, accesible via this link.

The data analysis presents some differences, especially in the outliers detection phase, that in this notebook has been covered. The imbalance detection is the same, and has been handled with the SMOTE.

After the data analysis, in the notebook has been covered only the supervised learning phase. In particular, SVC (support vector classification) and RandomForest Classifier have been used. They achieved respectivily, 96.7% and 98.3% of accuracy. Please note that is not present the cross validation. There is no grid search phase applied and neither unsupervised and semi-supervised learning.
